ce:section.ce:para:
Pressure and temperature were studied by comparing the QY of the CDots obtained under each set of conditions. The pressure did not seem to have a significant effect on the QY of the nanoparticles obtained, except for a slight decrease at 190 °C at low pressures (1 and 7 bar, respectively) compared to the increase at 17 bar, as shown in Fig. 3
                        A. However, photographs taken under UV lamp excitation (see Fig. 4
                        ) show a discontinued flow inside the microreactor channel due to the formation of bubbles, both at 1 and 7 bar, because the working temperature is well above the boiling point of the solvent. This could lead to channel occlusion due to the deposition of solid particles on the walls and a less homogeneous reaction product due to the flow fluctuations created. However, a continuous and stable flow was observed at 17 bar, indicating that there was no water evaporation. No cartridges of higher back pressure were evaluated because of the working range limitations of the syringe pumps. However, high-pressure equipment would make it possible to work at higher pressures. Therefore, 17 bar was selected as the optimal pressure for the rest of the experiments.
